   ART
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   National Gallery of Art, Washington, D.C.: "The Passionate
Eye: Impressionist and Other Master Paintings From the
Collection of Emil G. Buhrle" -- The first exhibition in the
U.S. devoted to the collection of this Swiss industrialist
(1890-1956) includes 85 oil paintings and works on paper by
Italian, Dutch, French and Spanish artists. Represented are
early masters such as Frans Hals and Canaletto;
impressionists and post-impressionists such as Manet, Monet
and Gauguin; and 20th-century artists such as Kandinsky,
Matisse and Picasso. Fourth Street at Constitution Avenue NW,
May 6-July 15. The show then moves to the Montreal Museum of
Fine Arts, Aug. 3-Oct. 14; the Yokohama Museum of Art, Japan,
Nov. 2, 1990-Jan. 13, 1991; and the Royal Academy of Arts,
London, Feb. 1-April 14, 1991.
                                                                                                       

   National Museum of American History, Smithsonian
Institution, Washington, D.C.: "Information Age: People,
Information &amp; Technology" -- This $10 million,
14,000-square-foot show, on indefinite display, examines how
information technology has changed our society in the past
150 years. A complete computer network ties together
interactive work stations, video, films and radio recordings.
More than 700 artifacts are displayed along with graphics and
objects from the museum's collections -- the Morse telegraph,
components of Bell's first telephone, early personal
computers. 14th Street and Constitution Avenue NW.
                                                                                                       

   National Museum of Women in the Arts, Washington, D.C.:
"Elisabeth Frink: Sculpture and Drawings 1950-1990" -- Sixty
sculptures and 25 drawings by this British artist, best known
for her monumental cast bronze portrait heads, male figures,
birds and animals. 1250 York Avenue, through July 4.
                                                                                                       

   Baltimore Museum of Art: "Weston's Westons: Portraits and
Nudes" -- More than 100 vintage prints by Edward Weston
(1886-1958), focusing solely on Weston as a figurative
photographer. The nudes include the little known "Male Torso"
(circa 1918); the highly abstract prints of the 1920s and
'30s; his '30s nudes on the sand dunes at Oceano; and his
last, satiric works, such as "Civilian Defense" (1942). Art
Museum Drive, through June 10.

   China Institute in America, New York: "Clear as Crystal,
Red as Flame: Later Chinese Glass" -- Almost 70 pieces form a
comprehensive survey of the art of Chinese glassmaking from
the 14th to 19th centuries. The pieces range from clear glass
vessels to trompe l'oeil imitations of jade, turquoise,
porcelain and other precious materials. 125 East 65th Street,
through June 16.
                                                                                                       

   DANCE
                                                                                                       

   Tomov Folk Dance Ensemble -- Authentic dances from
Yugoslavia and the Balkans performed by some 40 dancers,
singers and musicians. The troupe, in anticipation of its
performing tour of southern Yugoslavia this summer,
highlights the many dances of Macedonia. Riverside Church
Theater, Riverside Drive at 122nd Street, New York. May 12 at
2:30 and 7:30. For tickets, write the Folkdance Foundation,
66-12 48th Ave., Woodside, N.Y. 11377.
                                                                                                       

   MUSIC
                                                                                                       

   Metropolitan Opera: Sharon Sweet, a newcomer to the
company, sings Leonora in Verdi's "Il Trovatore." Franco
Bonisolli sings her troubadour. Lincoln Center, 65th and
Broadway, New York. May 2 and 5.
                                                                                                       

   Otowa Yurikago Kai, Japan's leading children's chorus,
makes its American debut at Carnegie Hall as part of the 30th
anniversary celebration of the sister city relationship
between Tokyo and New York. The 30 children who've made the
trip range in age from three to 17 years. They will performe
ancestral and contemporary Japanese folk songs, with half the
proceeds going to the United National Children's Fund. 57th
Street and Seventh Avenue, (212) 247-7800.
                                                                                                       

   ORRA, a music organization devoted to producing and
performing works of contemporary composers, presents
"Rimshot," a new satirical opera by Russell Currie about the
life of a ficticious rock drummer, Joe Rimshot. Based on the
play "Best" by Scott Speed, the show explores the elusive
nature of fame and popularity in the music biz. The libretto
is by Ron Singer, Jennifer Johanos directs, and the Orra
Chamber Ensemble provides the accompaniment. Pace Downtown
Theater, Schimmel Center for the Arts, Pace University, Pace
Plaza, New York. May 10-12. (212) 620-4294.
                                                                                                       

   Opera Delaware presents Mozart's "The Abduction From the
Seraglio," set in exotic 18th-century Turkey. It stars Evelyn
de la Rosa as Constanze and tenor James R. Longacre as
Belmonte. Stephen Lord conducts and Sally Stunkel directs.
Grand Opera House, 818 Market Street, Wilmington. May 5, 11
and 12. (302) 652-5577.
